04331nam a22006735i 9780271077338DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710773387 a10.1515/97802710773382doi  a(DE-B1597)583842  a(OCoLC)1269268851  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aQC380 7aHIS0100202bisacsh04a535.321 aChen-Morris, Raz, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMeasuring Shadows :bKepler's Optics of Invisibility /cRaz Chen-Morris. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b12 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tintroduction -- tone. The New Optical Narrative: Light, Camera Obscura, and the Astronomer's Wings -- ttwo. "Seeing with My Own Eyes": Introducing the New Foundations of Scientific Knowledge -- tthree. The Content of Kepler's Visual Language: Abstraction, Representation, and Recognition -- tfour."Non tanquam Pictor, sed tanquam Mathematicus": Kepler's Pictures and the Art of Painting -- tfive. Reading the Book of Nature: Allegories, Emblems, and Geometrical Diagrams -- tsix. Nothing and the Ends of Renaissance Science -- tpostscript -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Measuring Shadows, Raz Chen-Morris demonstrates that a close study of Kepler's Optics is essential to understanding his astronomical work and his scientific epistemology. He explores Kepler's radical break from scientific and epistemological traditions and shows how the seventeenth-century astronomer posited new ways to view scientific truth and knowledge. Chen-Morris reveals how Kepler's ideas about the formation of images on the retina and the geometrics of the camera obscura, as well as his astronomical observations, advanced the argument that physical reality could only be described through artificially produced shadows, reflections, and refractions.Breaking from medieval and Renaissance traditions that insisted upon direct sensory perception, Kepler advocated for instruments as mediators between the eye and physical reality, and for mathematical language to describe motion. It was only through this kind of knowledge, he argued, that observation could produce certainty about the heavens. Not only was this conception of visibility crucial to advancing the early modern understanding of vision and the retina, but it affected how people during that period approached and understood the world around them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGeometrical opticsxHistory. 0aSciencexPhilosophyxHistoryy17th century. 0aScience, Renaissance. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Western.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311074524540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271077338zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271077338423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271077338/original  a978-3-11-074524-5  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK